of People\[CloseCurlyQuote]s\\nCommissars.\\n\\nThe meeting-place was a \
theatre, in which, under the old r\[EAcute]gime, to\\naudiences of officers \
and glittering ladies, amateur presentations of\\nthe latest French comedy \
had once taken place.\\n\\nAt first the place filled with the \
intellectuals--those who lived near\\nthe centre of the town. Nogin spoke, \
and most of his listeners were\\nplainly with him. It was very late before \
the workers arrived; the\\nworking-class quarters were on the outskirts of \
