nGROWING ARROGANCE OF THE REACTIONARIES\\n\\nSeptember 18th. The Cadet \
Shulgin, writing in a Kiev newspaper, said\\nthat the Provisional Government\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s declaration that Russia was a\\nRepublic constituted a \
gross abuse of its powers. \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]We cannot admit\\neither a \
Republic, or the present Republican Government.... And we are\\nnot sure that \
we want a Republic in Russia....\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]\\n\\nOctober 23d. At \
a meeting of the Cadet party held at Riazan, M.\\nDukhonin declared, \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]On March 1st we must establish a \
Constitutional\\nMonarchy. We must not reject the legitimate heir to the \
throne,\\nMikhail Alexandrovitch....\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]\\n\\nOctober \
27th. Resolution passed by the Conference of Business Men at\\nMoscow:\\n\\n\
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]The Conference... insists that the Provisional \
Government take the\\nfollowing immediate measures in the Army:\\n\\n\
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]1. Forbidding of all political propaganda; the Army \
must be out of\\npolitics.\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]2. Propaganda of \
antinational and international ideas and theories\\ndeny the necessity for \
armies, and hurt discipline; it should be\\nforbidden, and all propagandists \
punished....\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]3. The function of the Army \
Committees must be limited to economic\\nquestions exclusively. All their \
decisions should be confirmed by\\ntheir superior officers, who have the \
right to dissolve the\\nCommittees at any time....\\n\\n\
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]4. The salute to be reestablished, and made \
obligatory. Full\\nreestablishment of disciplinary power in the hands of \
officers, with\\nright of review of \
sentence....\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]5. Expulsion from the Corps of \
Officers of those who dishonour it by\\nparticipating in the movement of the \
soldier-masses, which teaches\\nthem disobedience.... Reestablishment for \
this purpose of the Courts of\\nHonor....\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]6. The \
Provisional Government should take the necessary measures to\\nmake possible \
the return to the army of Generals and other officers\\nunjustly discharged \
under the influence of Committees, and other\\nirresponsible \
organisations....\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]\\n\\n\\nAPPENDIX TO CHAPTER \
II\\n\\n1.\\n\\nThe Kornilov revolt is treated in detail in my forthcoming \
volume,\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Kornilov to Brest-Litovsk.\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] The responsibility of Kerensky for the\\nsituation \
which gave rise to Kornilov\[CloseCurlyQuote]s attempt is now pretty \
clearly\\nestablished. Many apologists for Kerensky say that he knew \
of\\nKornilov\[CloseCurlyQuote]s plans, and by a trick drew him out \
prematurely, and then\\ncrushed him. Even Mr. A. J. Sack, in his book, \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]The Birth of the\\nRussian Democracy,\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] says:\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Several things... \
are almost certain. The first is that Kerensky knew\\nabout the movement of \
several detachments from the Front toward\\nPetrograd, and it is possible \
that as Prime Minister and Minister of\\nWar, realising the growing \
Bolshevist danger, he called for them....\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]\\n\\nThe \
only flaw in that argument is that there was no \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Bolshevist\\ndanger\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] at that \
time, the Bolsheviki still being a powerless minority\\nin the Soviets, and \
their leaders in jail or hiding.\\n\\n2.\\n\\nDEMOCRATIC CONFERENCE\\n\\nWhen \
