GORBUNOV.\\n\\n                        *     *     *     *     *\\n\\nOn \
December 3d the Council of People\[CloseCurlyQuote]s Commissars resolved \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]to reduce\\nthe salaries of functionaries and \
employees in all Government\\ninstitutions and establishments, general or \
special, without\\nexception.\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]\\n\\nTo begin with, the \
Council fixed the salary of a People\[CloseCurlyQuote]s Commissar\\nat 500 \
rubles per month, with 100 rubles additional for each grown\\nmember of the \
family incapable of work....\\n\\nThis was the highest salary paid to any \
Government official....\\n\\n4.\\n\\nCountess Panina was arrested and brought \
to trial before the first\\nSupreme Revolutionary Tribunal. The trial is \
described in the chapter\\non \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Revolutionary Justice\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] in my forthcoming volume, \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Kornilov to\\nBrist-Litovsk.\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] \
The prisoner was sentenced to \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]return the money, \
and\\nthen be liberated to the public contempt.\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] In \
other words, she was\\nset free!\\n\\n5.\\n\\nRIDICULE OF THE NEW R\
\[CapitalEAcute]GIME\\n\\nFrom _Drug Naroda_ (Menshevik), November \
18th:\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]The story of the \[OpenCurlyQuote]immediate \
peace\[CloseCurlyQuote] of the Bolsheviki reminds us of a\\njoyous \
moving-picture film.... Neratov runs--Trotzky pursues; Neratov\\nclimbs a \
wall, Trotzky too; Neratov dives into the water--Trotzky\\nfollows; Neratov \
climbs onto the roof--Trotzky right behind him;\\nNeratov hides under the \
bed--and Trotzky has him! He has him!\\nNaturally, peace is immediately \
signed....\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]All is empty and silent at the \
Ministry of Foreign Affairs. The\\ncouriers are respectful, but their faces \
wear a caustic expression....\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]How about arresting \
an ambassador and signing an armistice or a\\nPeace Treaty with him? But they \
are strange folk, these ambassadors.\\nThey keep silent just as if they had \
heard nothing. Hola, hola,\\nEngland, France, Germany! We have signed an \
armistice with you! Is it\\npossible that you know nothing about it? \
Nevertheless, it has been\\npublished in all the papers and posted on all the \
walls. On a\\nBolshevik\[CloseCurlyQuote]s word of honour, Peace has been \
signed. We\[CloseCurlyQuote]re not asking\\nmuch of you; you just have to \
write two words....\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]The ambassadors remain \
silent. The Powers remain silent. All is\\nempty and silent in the office of \
the Minister of Foreign \
Affairs.\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\[OpenCurlyQuote]Listen,\
\[CloseCurlyQuote] says Robespierre-Trotzky to his assistant \
Marat-Uritzky,\\n\[OpenCurlyQuote]run over to the British Ambassador\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s, tell him we\[CloseCurlyQuote]re proposing\\npeace!\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\[OpenCurlyQuote]Go yourself,\
\[CloseCurlyQuote] says Marat-Uritzky. \[OpenCurlyQuote]He\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \
not receiving.\[CloseCurlyQuote]\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\[OpenCurlyQuote]\
Telephone him, then.\[CloseCurlyQuote]\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\
\[OpenCurlyQuote]I\[CloseCurlyQuote]ve tried. The receiver\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \
off the hook.\[CloseCurlyQuote]\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\[OpenCurlyQuote]\
Send him a telegram.\[CloseCurlyQuote]\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\
\[OpenCurlyQuote]I did.\[CloseCurlyQuote]\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\
\[OpenCurlyQuote]Well, with what result?\[CloseCurlyQuote]\\n\\n\
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Marat-Uritzky sighs and does not answer. \
Robespierre-Trotzky spits\\nfuriously into the corner....\\n\\n\
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\[OpenCurlyQuote]Listen, Marat,\[CloseCurlyQuote] \
recommences Trotzky, after a moment. \[OpenCurlyQuote]We must\\nabsolutely \
show that we\[CloseCurlyQuote]re conducting an active foreign policy. \
How\\ncan we do that?\[CloseCurlyQuote]\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\
\[OpenCurlyQuote]Launch another decree about arresting Neratov,\
\[CloseCurlyQuote] answers Uritzky,\\nwith a profound air.\\n\\n\
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\[OpenCurlyQuote]Marat, you\[CloseCurlyQuote]re a \
blockhead!\[CloseCurlyQuote] cries Trotzky. All of a sudden he\\narises, \
terrible and majestic, looking at this moment like\\nRobespierre.\\n\\n\
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\[OpenCurlyQuote]Write, Uritzky!\[CloseCurlyQuote] he \
says with severity. \[OpenCurlyQuote]Write a letter to the\\nBritish \
ambassador, a registered letter with receipt demanded. Write!\\nI also will \
write! The peoples of the world await an immediate \
peace!\[CloseCurlyQuote]\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]In the enormous and \
empty Ministry of Foreign Affairs are to be\\nheard only the sound of two \
typewriters. With his own hands Trotzky\\nis conducting an active foreign \
policy....\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]\\n\\n6.\\n\\nON THE QUESTION OF AN \
AGREEMENT\\n\\nTo the Attention of All Workers and All \
Soldiers.\\n\\nNovember 11th, in the club of the Preobrazhensky Regiment, was \
held\\nan extraordinary meeting of representatives of all the units of \
the\\nPetrograd garrison.\\n\\nThe meeting was called upon the initiative of \
the Preobrazhensky and\\nSemionovsky Regiments, for the discussion of the \
question as to which\\nSocialist parties are for the power of the Soviets, \
which are\\nagainst, which are for the people, which against, and if an \
agreement\\nbetween them is possible.\\n\\nThe representatives of the \
_Tsay-ee-kah,_ of the Municipal Duma, of\\nthe Avksentiev Peasants\
\[CloseCurlyQuote] Soviets, and of all the political parties\\nfrom the \
Bolsheviki to the Populist Socialists, were invited to \
the\\nmeeting.\\n\\nAfter long deliberation, having heard the declarations of \
all\\nparties and organisations, the meeting by a tremendous majority\\nof \
votes agreed that only the Bolsheviki and the Left \
Socialist\\nRevolutionaries are for the people, and that all the other \
parties\\nare only attempting, under cover of seeking an agreement, to \
deprive\\nthe people of the conquests won in the days of the great Workers\
\[CloseCurlyQuote] and\\nPeasants\[CloseCurlyQuote] Revolution of \
November.\\n\\nHere is the text of the resolution carried at this meeting of \
the\\nPetrograd garrison, by 61 votes against 11, and 12 not voting:\\n\\n\
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]The garrison conference, summoned at the initiative of \
the\\nSemionovsky and Preobrazhensky Regiments, on hearing \
the\\nrepresentatives of all the Socialist parties and \
popular\\norganisations on the question of an agreement between the different\
\\npolitical parties finds that:\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]1. The \
representatives of the _Tasy-ee-kah,_ the representatives of\\nthe Bolshevik \
party and the Left Socialist Revolutionaries, declared\\ndefinitely that they \
stand for a Government of the Soviets, for the\\ndecrees on Land, Peace and \
Workers\[CloseCurlyQuote] Control of Industry, and that\\nupon this platform \
they are willing to agree with all the Socialist\\nparties.\\n\\n\
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]2. At the same time the representatives of the other \
parties\\n(Mensheviki, Socialist Revolutionaries) either gave no answer at \
all,\\nor declared simply that they were opposed to the power of the \
Soviets\\nand against the decrees on Land, Peace and \
Workers\[CloseCurlyQuote] Control.\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]In view of \
this the meeting resolves:\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\[OpenCurlyQuote]1. To \
express severe censure of all parties which, under cover of\\nan agreement, \
wish practically to annul the popular conquests of the\\nRevolution of \
November.\\n\\n\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]2. To express full confidence in the \
_Tsay-ee-kah_ and the Council\\nof People\[CloseCurlyQuote]s Commissars, and \
to promise them complete support.\[CloseCurlyQuote]\\n\\n\
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]At the same time the meeting deems it necessary that \
the comrades\\nLeft Socialist Revolutionaries should enter the People\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s Government.\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]\\n\\n7.\\n\\nWINE \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]POGROMS\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]\\n\\nIt was afterward \
discovered that there was a regular organisation,\\nmaintained by the Cadets, \
for provoking rioting among the soldiers.\\nThere would be telephone messages \
to the different barracks,\\nannouncing that wine was being given away at \
such and such an\\naddress, and when the soldiers arrived at the spot an \
individual\\nwould point out the location of the cellar....\\n\\nThe Council \
of People\[CloseCurlyQuote]s Commissars appointed a Commissar for the\\nFight \
Against Drunkenness, who, besides mercilessly putting down the\\nwine riots, \
destroyed hundreds of thousands of bottles of liquor. The\\nWinter Palace \
cellars, containing rare vintages valued at more than\\nfive million dollars, \
were at first flooded, and then the liquor was\\nremoved to Cronstadt and \
destroyed.\\n\\nIn this work the Cronstadt sailors, \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]flower and pride of the\\nrevolutionary forces,\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] as Trotzky called them, acquitted themselves\\nwith \
iron self-dicipline....\\n\\n8.\\n\\nSPECULATORS\\n\\nTwo orders concerning \
them:\\n\\n  _Council of People\[CloseCurlyQuote]s Commissars_\\n\\n  _To the \
Military Revolutionary Committee_\\n\\nThe disorganisation of the food supply \
created by the war, and the\\nlack of system, is becoming to the last degree \
acute, thanks to the\\nspeculators, marauders and their followers on the \
railways, in the\\nsteamship offices, forwarding offices, etc.\\n\\nTaking \
advantage of the nation\[CloseCurlyQuote]s greatest misfortunes, these \
criminal\\nspoliators are playing with the health and life of millions \
of\\nsoldiers and workers, for their own benefit.\\n\\nSuch a situation \
cannot be borne a single day longer.\\n\\nThe Council of People\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s Commissars proposes to the Military\\nRevolutionary \
Committee to take the most decisive measures towards\\nthe uprooting of \
speculation, sabotage, hiding of supplies,\\nfraudulent detention of cargoes, \
etc.\\n\\nAll persons guilty of such actions shall be subject, by \
special\\norders of the Military Revolutionary Committee, to immediate arrest\
\\nand confinement in the prisons of Cronstadt, pending their\\narraignment \
before the Revolutionary Tribunal.\\n\\nAll the popular organisations are \
invited to cooperate in the\\nstruggle against the spoliators of food \
supplies.\\n\\n                _President of the Council of People\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s Commissaries._\\n                                        \
